BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 640.40 Tm (A single JSON object for a student, then a JSON array of students, with the parts colour-coded.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 626.90 3.00 35.50 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 615.90 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 599.90 Tm (Now let's meet the language web services speak - JSON. It stands for JavaScript Object Notation,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 584.70 Tm (but do not worry about the name. What matters is that it is a simple, lightweight text format for) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 569.50 Tm (data, and every programming language can read it. You will be staring at JSON in your testing tool) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 554.30 Tm (in about twenty minutes, so let me make it click now.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 534.10 Tm (Look at the single student on screen. See the curly braces? They wrap one object - one record,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 518.90 Tm (one student. Inside, we have pairs - a key on the left, always in quotes, then a colon, then a value.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 503.70 Tm (Like 'firstName' colon 'Ravi'. Commas separate the pairs. And the values can be text in quotes,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 488.50 Tm (plain numbers, or true-slash-false for yes-no.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 468.30 Tm (Now the second example uses square brackets - those make a list, or array. So a response with) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 453.10 Tm (several students is just a list of those objects. Easy.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 432.90 Tm (And here is the part that will make you smile - you will not write any of this by hand. Spring Boot) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 417.70 Tm (uses a library called Jackson that automatically turns your Java Student object into JSON on the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 402.50 Tm (way out, and turns incoming JSON back into a Java object on the way in. You hand it a Java) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 387.30 Tm (object, the caller receives JSON. That automatic conversion has a name - serialization - and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 372.10 Tm (Spring does it for you.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 356.90 3.00 265.00 re f
BT /F2 15.00 Tf 0.100 0.100 0.120 rg 1 0 0 1 58.00 337.90 Tm (Slide 6 - Key web service terminology) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 320.90 496.00 1.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.420 0.420 0.460 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 304.90 Tm (ON SCREEN) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 288.90 Tm (Four cards with analogies: service provider, service consumer, synchronous, asynchronous. A key box on) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 275.40 Tm (loose coupling.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 261.90 3.00 49.00 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 250.90 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 234.90 Tm (A few vocabulary words you will hear constantly - and each comes with an everyday analogy, so) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 219.70 Tm (they stick. Think of a restaurant.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 199.50 Tm (First, the service provider - the app that offers the service and answers requests. That is the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 184.30 Tm (kitchen that cooks the food. Today, your Spring Boot API is the provider. Second, the service) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 169.10 Tm (consumer - the app that calls the service and uses its data. That is the customer who orders. Your) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 153.90 Tm (testing tool, a browser, or a phone app are consumers. Third, synchronous - the consumer asks) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 138.70 Tm (and then waits for the answer before doing anything else. That is standing at the counter until your) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 123.50 Tm (order is handed to you. And fourth, asynchronous - the consumer asks but does not wait; it carries) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 108.30 Tm (on and gets notified later. That is taking a buzzer and going to sit down until it buzzes.) Tj ET
